# Tables
You can generate a table in Latex from cells that have been defined with __Table__.
The syntax is the same as for an embedded table, except that instead of using
you use

To generate the table cells in the example below, the syntax __Table__(

### Example
This will generate the following table:

The first parameter is the table number, followed by any optional parameters.
The actual table-cell content is defined with __Cell__() (without parentheses). If you give a custom number for __Cell__() (which is optional), Latex will refer to that instead of the number given for the __Table__(). The optional third parameter should be a name for the table cell, to be used in the template. Using the optional fourth parameter, which defaults to False, you can specify whether you want the cell to retain its __Cell__() contents or replace it with the table. The table caption defaults to the contents in the cell before it was referred to by __Table__(). If you want to specify a caption, you have to add it in by hand.
Note that you can use the parameters from __Cell__() inside the optional fourth parameter. In our example, lines 3 and 4 have no __Cell__(), so they are simply numbered automatically when the table is formed; instead, line 5 contains a custom number for the cell, which allows for finer control of cell numbering.
In case you were wondering, yes, you can have multiple __Cell__() per __Table__(), with corresponding different numbers for each of them. Also noteworthy is that line 1 is the last line without __Cell__() in it, making it automatically the last table cell. Finally, note that __Cell__() will use latex.math.rcfonts to output inline maths (i.e., 1+2), other Latex code will not. The following table is a visual representation:

Here is an example of usage:
Note first that it is important to have __Table__() defined before using __Cell__(). __Cell__() uses __Table__() to automatically get the number of the table cell, so having __Table__() before it will result in a reference error. Also note that __Cell__() automatically numbers the table cell, so you would have to explicitly add line 2's cell number manually if there were more table cells

In the treatments column we note that the patient is not using multivitamins or iron supplements. We then go across and check that the stage is 1-3 and ER/PR negative. The tumor histology, in our example is invasive ductal breast carcinoma. We also go across checking that if the tumor size is 3, stage is 3, and the tumor type is invasive ductal breast carcinoma then it is HER2 positive.

For most of the cases it is easier to start by going across to each of the conditions to determine whether it meets a given criterion in the inclusion/exclusion criteria. Then once you have done that, go again through the inclusion/exclusion criteria looking at the positive indications.
This is the way this is usually done in practice. For example, for the clinical trial we would start by looking at the tumor characteristics and find the criteria that the patient has positive characteristics for e.g., invasive ductal breast carcinoma. We then proceed by going through the remaining conditions, some of which will exclude the patient but then we go back and see if any positive entries in the remaining conditions remain and that takes us to HER2 positivity. 
Always start by first checking all the relevant conditions against your patient and then see if there are any positives remaining. As you can see in this case there are no conditions remaining with a positive indication.</s><s>

Either unilateral or bilateral fracture of both the greater trochanters occurring in a thin  women aged over 55 years.

women with unilateral HF who are incapable of a complete 3-month follow-up or a willingness to drop out.

### Task: Summary
In this task, you will summarize the clinical study protocol. 
This should appear on a new, separate block, and start with a summary of the whole protocol in a few sentences. This should include the basic aim of the study, the hypotheses, the main objectives and a short explanation of the methodology employed, the eligibility and exclusion criteria, and numbers of planned participants. Try to focus on 1 or 2 sentences that describe the overarching purpose of the clinical study protocol, and make sure that this summary contains the keywords and phrases that are also used in the title of the protocol, which is a required field in the OSIRIS template. The summary should be written in the third person (use he/she/it rather than we), and should not contain names of any specific authors or organization.
Suggested layout for summary: 
Here is an example summary taken from a protocol for a randomized controlled trial of a new ultrasound technique to evaluate rotator cuff tears: 

Rationale: Despite advances in non-operative management of the shoulder, diagnostic tests are sometimes needed in clinical settings to improve patient management. Standard MRI imaging might not be readily available in all settings and new ultrasound techniques are being developed to make imaging easier and more available. This study aims to compare a novel ultrasound technique to evaluate rotator cuff tears against a standard MRI reading while blinded to any other imaging findings.
Objective: To evaluate the intra- and inter-observer reproducibility of a novel ultrasound technique for the evaluation of the rotator cuff.
Study design: A multi-centered randomized controlled trial.
Intervention: Patients will undergo a novel ultrasound technique as well as MRI evaluation of the rotator cuff.
Control: Patients will only undergo MRI evaluation of the rotator cuff and not the novel ultrasound technique.
Outcome: The primary outcome measure will be the intra-observer and inter-observer agreement of the novel ultrasound technique for the evaluation of the rotator cuff compared to the MRI evaluation.
Sample size calculation: The necessary sample size has not been calculated.
Inclusion and exclusion criteria: Eligible participants will include non-operative stabilization

That is to say, it is also necessary not only to identify the patient is not eligible (0) for the clinical trial but also the reason why the patient is not eligible. 
If the clinical trial includes inclusion criteria that do not apply to the patient, you should report at least one reason for not eligibility in the second part of the eligibility report. 
In this case, you should report the reason for ineligibility, e.g., the patient's age is not included in the age criteria of the trial.</s><s>

Part 4: Evaluation Scripts
To evaluate the inclusion criteria of a clinical trial, one can generate an evaluation script.
A clinical trial may have a lot of specific inclusion criteria. You may list them all or only the most stringent.
For example, in the previous clinical trial, you could write: 
If the patient is older than 54 years: [0] Excluded
If the patient is older than 54 years and has a body mass index greater than 30: [2] Eligible
If the patient is < 54 years old: [1] Not Relevant
Or you could use a form to tick off the boxes.
You could also code the inclusion criteria by "YES" and "NO" and list them down, e.g.,
YES NO
Age < 54 years Older than 54 years YES YES
Hypercholesterolemia YES NO
NVDs YES NO
Gallstones YES NO
Then you should repeat the summary of the inclusion criteria at the end, e.g., 
Inclusion Criteria:
- patients aged 18-75 yo scheduled for laparoscopic cholecystectomy YES NO
...</s><s>

Epstein-Barr Virus (EBV) is one of the most common virus in human. EBV causes infectious mononucleosis in about 90% of infection. Though the symptoms of mononucleosis are self-limiting, but can sometimes be severe. The symptoms can be divided into infectious, and symptoms related to hyper-reactive immune response.
The incubation period of mononucleosis is 4-7 weeks. The most common mode of transmission is through Saliva. The virus may be present in the patient's saliva with low viral load. Contact with saliva allows it to activate B cells from lymphoid tissue. Infection occur when this activated B cell infects other B cells. B cells infected with EBV can cause hyperplasia and atypia, which eventually lead to the formation of tumors such Burkitt's lymphoma, Hodgkin's lymphoma and Nasopharyngeal carcinoma.  The prevalence of EBV infection increases with age. People younger than 25 years old have a 25% chance of having EBV infection, while adults above 25 have 90% chance of having the infection. 
Common complication of EBV infection are:  
Gastritis and peptic ulcer (due to hypersecretion of gastrin and gastric acid) Pneumonia (caused by hyper-inflammation response) Encephalitis (due to CNS infiltration by activated B cells)  Meningitis (due to CNS infiltration by activated B cells) Hepatitis (due to hyperglycemia and hyper-inflammation response) Transient hypothyroidism 
There are no specific EBV infection, but EBV can affect several organ system. Therefore, EBV infection must be ruled out for other diseases that have a common EBV association.

==== Explanation of a single clinical trial assessment ====
In this example, the patient does not meet the inclusion criteria of the clinical trial, and is therefore excluded by the trial's exclusion criteria. You can refer to the clinical trial sheet for the detailed inclusion/exclusion criteria. 

Patient's age: The patient's age <60 years is not met (age inclusion criterion #1).
Patient's HBsAg: The patient has a positive HBsAg, which is not met (HBsAg inclusion criterion #1).
Drug treatment: The patient is on vitamin D. Vitamin D is not an option in the clinical trial for the patient (exclusion criterion #6).
Albumin: The patient has an albumin level of 3, which is not met (alphabetical list of inclusion/exclusion criteria).


==== General explanation: what are you doing here? ====
In the above examples of clinical trial scripts and assessment scripts, I've provided the English translation of the patient note and the clinical trial sheet.
However, sometimes the actual contents of these notes are not available for you, hence you need to make a good attempt at understanding the medical data given by yourself.
Below is an example of a patient note of a patient with congestive heart failure. You need to do a clinical trial assessment to determine the patient's eligibility (trial-level assessment) based on the inclusion/exclusion criteria of a hypothetical trial.



Transporter function of endothelial cells of heart microvasculature is damaged leading to impaired interstitial fluid reabsorption with congestion in end ventricle and finally resulting in HF. In HF patients, LVEDP tends to be normal or low. 


[TRIAL-LEVEL ASSESSMENT] 
Inclusion criteria #11: LVEDP is not specified as an inclusion criterion in the clinical trial.

In the hypothetical clinical trial you're assessing the patient for, it is probably listed to avoid including patients with LVEDP < xx mmHg, which we typically consider as exclusion criteria to avoid patients with pulmonary or renal congestion

The purpose of the code is to simulate a real-life scenario to educate and guide a healthcare-provider through the inclusion/exclusion criteria and the matching process with a clinical trial.
The code goes through the matching of patient information to clinical trial inclusion/exclusion criteria and the respective level of eligibility on a scale.  
The first part takes in a set of patient information, the second part defines the clinical trial and third part assesses the level of eligibility. 
At the end, a score is generated as a three-item list of the outcome of criteria matching.</s><s>

Here are the steps:
Identify relevant sections of the patient note and clinical trial: Extract [CLINICAL TRIAL] and [PATIENT NOTE] from the question, put them into a code block, and run the code. Assign relevant values to variables. 
For the clinical trial, identify a sensible section description, namely "The purpose of this study", extract it, and call it trialtitle. For the inclusion criteria, identify "Inclusion Criteria", extract it, and call it inclcrit.

Determine relevant variables: Make a list of the sections of the clinical trial that you might want to extract information from and name the respective codes, e.g., trialinfo for anything that you want to extract from the title, summary, etc., inclinfo for anything that you want to extract from the inclusion criteria.

Extract information from the clinical trial: Extract any information from the clinical trial using code blocks. You might want to extract title, study type (if any), disease name, date of submission, etc. For information like the inclusion criteria, you need to split it by semicolons and extract the individual criteria by using multiple code blocks. 

Identify which section contains the actual inclusion criteria: Identify the text "Inclusion Criteria" or anything that might be a list. It can be anywhere: before or after the statement, in a separate section, or at the end of the text.

Extract the inclusion criteria: Extract the text "Inclusion Criteria" and everything after up to a semicolon using a code block call it inclcriter. 

Identify main points: You need to determine whether there are different types of inclusion criteria, what the main criteria are, etc. Write these main points in a code block, e.g., inclcritsummary.

Check comprehensiveness: If the inclusion critiera in the clinical trial are not entirely consistent with what is extracted, either the extraction or the interpretation is wrong. Check comprehensiveness by comparing to the clinical trial text, e.g., with code blocks inclcriter-text and inclcrit-text.

This section should include a brief (one-sentence) description of the overall experimental design and some early methods used. This section may be skipped if the methods have been fully described in the Introduction, or in a previous section. For example,

Subjects were allocated to treatment groups using randomly permuted blocks of 4 with a block size of 3.

[INST] Hello. You are a helpful assistant for clinical trial recruitment. Your task is to compare a given patient note and the inclusion criteria of a clinical trial to determine the patient's eligibility. The factors that allow someone to participate in a clinical study are called inclusion criteria. They are based on characteristics such as age, gender, the type and stage of a disease, previous treatment history, and other medical conditions. 
The assessment of eligibility has a three-point scale: 0) Excluded (patient meets inclusion criteria, but is excluded on the grounds of the trial's exclusion criteria); 1) Not relevant (patient does not have sufficient information to qualify for the trial); and 2) Eligible (patient meets inclusion criteria and exclusion criteria do not apply). 
Patients who are Excluded are so by the Trial's criteria while patients who are Not relevant are evaluated based on their information and the inclusion criteria is not mentioned as they did not need any additional information.

She claims mild dyspnea after climbing 3 floors, no dyspnea at rest and no angina (New York Heart Association class 2). She is diagnosed with cardiomyopathy that will be treated with ACE inhibitors and Beta blockers. Her takes 70/30 Insulin and vitamin D supplement

def get_paragraph(sentences):
    assert len(sentences) > 0
    last = sentences[0][-1][1]
    paragraphs = [last]
    for s, ss in sentences:
        if last == s:
            paragraphs.append(ss)
        else:
            paragraphs[-1].extend(ss)
    return paragraphs


def get_tokens(paragraphs, separators=["."]):

    return [separator.join(r.split(separator) for r in sentences if r) for sentences in paragraphs for separator in separators]

To give just one example here of a good way to write out the decision-making process of assessing the patients eligibility:

Hello. You are a helpful assistant for clinical trial recruitment. Your task is to compare a given patient note and the inclusion criteria of a clinical trial to determine the patient's eligibility. The factors that allow someone to participate in a clinical study are called inclusion criteria. They are based on characteristics such as age, gender, the type and stage of a disease, previous treatment history, and other medical conditions.

To find the patient's eligibility, I will check if the patient meets each of the inclusion criteria under the three point scale of (0) Excluded, (1) Not relevant or (2) Eligible. 

Checking for exclusion criteria: The patient does not meet exclusion criterion 1 as they have [EXCLUDED: 1]. Now we move to criterion 2 which states [EXCLUDED: 2]. We can continue in this fashion until there are no more exclusion criteria. However, there is no further exclusion criteria listed, only inclusion criteria, so I will begin evaluating the patient's eligibility with those. 

Checking for inclusion criteria: The patient is eligible for inclusion criteria 1 as they [ELIGIBLE: 1]. Next we come to criteria 2 which states [ELIGIBLE: 2]. We continue in this fashion until there are no more inclusion criteria. However, there are no remaining inclusion criteria, so the patient is fully eligible.

Aspirin, however, can also cause damage to the stomach and/or intestinal lining leading to the development of erosions (small sores) and/or ulcers (large sores). Erosions may cause bleeding (bleeding ulcers) and/or perforations (holes in the stomach). Acetaminophen, often referred by the brand name, Tylenol, is also used to treat minor pains but is not commonly recognized to cause damage to the stomach lining. Many patients often take both of these medications together. While the effects on the stomach lining of each medication, when used alone, are known, the effects of both medications, when used together, are not. The purpose of this study is to show whether or not the collective effects of both aspirin and acetaminophen, when used together, increase the damage on the stomach lining when compared to either medication alone.

A 67-year-old healthy woman ... 
Is this inclusion criteria exclusionary?
I.e., is the disease she has (which we aren't told, but assume it's the flu shot target population (i.e., influenza) for the trial) an exclusionary one? 
I.e., is the type of vaccination she has - flu shot - part of the inclusion/exclusion criteria set? 
Or is this trial merely screening for risk factors - which would be "not relevant" anyway? 
Finally - is it relevant that she's menopausal?
Etc...
How specific must we be with the requirements of our criteria?  E.g., in the real world would the inclusion/exclusion criteria for flu shots necessarily include/exclude a woman with 4 children (i.e., does the vaccine manufacturer intend that population to receive them, which is to say: Is it age-appropriate?; and does her profession constitute a high-risk group? (i.e., is there a higher likelihood that she would be infected?)) - or is this all "irrelevant" as she doesn't work in that field anymore?  If we consider "menopausal", do we consider her status in it, or consider it irrelevant since she used to have the status, but no longer does? 
I.e., would it be better if I went on to read every single line of the clinical trial document in an attempt to understand the goals of the clinical trial, why the flu shot has been chosen, what we might hope to learn from the conclusions, in order to help guide us in identifying more precise inclusion and exclusion criteria? 
Why is a clinical trial framed in a fluffy manner as "To evaluate the demographic characteristics of children suffering From ..." - which is to say: is this why the flu shot is chosen as a study population, or are there other reasons?  Is the manufacturer a concerned member of the community who just wants to know how often certain diseases are contracted by their product's target population? And if so, why bother with the clinical trial?  Wouldn't survey data serve the same purpose? Or is this a more academic exercise? Etc...

4752.output:
It is also important who is responsible for performing these checks, i.e., the reviewer is often responsible for these assessments and reports (but not always). However, it is even more important who produces the document. The reviewer should only be responsible for reporting (though they can suggest improvements) and should not be asked to produce templates for the patient (which can be very time-consuming). 
If the reviewer is responsible for producing the template, then it is extremely important for the reviewer to understand patient-level eligibility on the one hand and study-level and trial-level eligibility on the other hand. For example, a reviewer can assess trial-level eligibility and report that a patient is possibly eligible (output `1) Possibly Eligible`). However, it is not the role of the reviewer to assess patient-level eligibility, which can be much more complicated. The template can therefore include an output `Study-level eligibility = 0) Excluded`, which can make the code clearer for the reviewer.

Dissatisfaction: The  patient dissatisfied with her body shape

History:    The patient has no prior pregnancies  
Exercise:     The patient rarely exercises and movement seems to be hard for her     
Four-square step test:   The patient is able to complete   the four-square step test in less than 15 seconds.    
BP:  The patient's blood pressure is within the reference ranges 
Hr: The patient's heart rate is  within the reference ranges  
BMI: The patient's BMI is  within the reference ranges

TG:    The patient's triglycerides are  within the reference ranges 
Cholesterol:  The patient's total cholesterol is within the reference ranges 
LDL:   The patient's low-density lipoprotein is   within the reference ranges 
HDL:    The patient's high-density lipoprotein is   within the reference ranges

The function that you are going to need is the following.
EligibilityLevel = 
Function [
    TailorMadeFunction, 
    TrialSubjectInformation, 
    EligibilityLevel, 
] 
where 
TrialSubjectInformation = 
Function [
    SubjectNote, 
    Identifier, 
    DateOfConsent, 
] 
and SubjectNote = 
Function [
    ListLine, 
    StringVar, 
] 
and 
ListLine = 
Function [
    ConsentLine, 
    Comments, 
    OutputTo, 
] 
and ConsentLine = 
Function [
    ListTable, 
    StringVar, 
    StringVar, 
] 
and ListTable = 
Function[
    Table, 
    String[title], 
    SingleColumn, 
    TableType -> nt_tabular, 
    
    InputTo -> {String[#1], SingleColumn}, 
    Padding -> {{0, 0, nil}, {4, 4, nil}}, 
    ColumnHeads -> {String[Name], String["Status"]},
    TableHeader -> LineBreak, 
    TableAlignments -> "Automatic"
    
    ] 
and Identity = 
Function[ 
    Name, 
    StringVar, 
] 
and DateOfConsent = 
Function[ 
    Name, 
    DateString, 
    DateStamp, 
] 
Finally let's implement the main function.
Example@EligibilityLevel[
    SubjectNote ->
        First Line, 
        Comments -> 
            "Second Line\nThird Line", 
        OutputTo -> "MedSira",

Note the three parts of the eligibility assessment, followed by the scoring. Your algorithm should produce a three-element array for the score, and if there's some reason for more complex scoring (like a 12-point scoring system for the SFEMG), the algorithm should produce a mapping from the scores to the words. Of course you'll need text descriptions for the individual elements in the eligibility array and/or mapping, etc., or this may be difficult to understand. If there is an overall threshold of 2/3 for example, the first point might be whether there's sufficient information to qualify, and this would lead to 1) Not relevant if not met and 2) Excluded if not sufficient information. 
I'll spare you my own algorithmic solution, but this is the algorithm you'd run on the example input above: 
Initialise all three array-elements of the score to -1 (outside the array) 
Read the patient note line-by-line and create an array of the sentences with their corresponding sentiment scores 
Iterate through the sentences 
    if the patient satisfies the inclusion criteria for the clinical trial
        assign the sentence a score of 1 
    else if the patient does not satisfy the inclusion criteria for the clinical trial, but the details of their condition are sufficient for assessment
        assign the sentence a score of 0.5 
    else if not enough information is given for assessment 
        assign the sentence a score of -1
    EndIter 
EndIter 
Iterate through the sentence scores and find the largest score 
    if it is 1 
        assign the overall Trial-level eligibility to 2) Eligible 
    EndIf 
Iterate through sentences and find the largest score 
    if it is 2 (and the largest score is not higher than 2) 
        assign the overall eligibility to 1) Not relevant 
    EndIf 
Iterate through sentences and find the largest score 
    if it is -1 
        assign the overall eligibility to 0) Excluded 
EndIter 
The final result should be: 
[0] => Array 
    (
    [0] => 0
    [1] => 2
    [2]

The patient is a 16-year-old girl recently diagnosed with myasthenia gravis, class IIa. She complains of diplopia and weakness affecting in her upper extremities. Summary: Cystic Fibrosis Related Diabetes has been identified by the CF community as one of the top ten priorities for CF
  research. In CF clinical decline due to dysglycemia begins early, prior to diagnosis of diabetes and increases mortality from pulmonary disease. There is presently no way to determine who, of those with dysglycemia, will experience clinical compromise. However, the CF Center in Milan has found that measurable
  age- and sex-dependent variables on oral glucose tolerance testing (OGTT) predict β-cell failure-the primary driver of decline in CF. ==== Exercises for chapter 2: Recognizing Abnormalcy and Categorizing Findings ====
I will provide short descriptions and expect you to come up with codes on your own. These aren't comprehensive descriptions, I would just expect these to act as prompts for your codes and categories and for you to take the descriptions and incorporate them however is relevant in your own system of categorization.
Much like how a human doctor would work, we don't simply have standard categories such as "muscular pain" or "anxiety" without considering the specifics. 
Also I encourage you to do at least some basic research to learn at least some of the medical terminology. Look up some of these to get ideas. Ask around and see what people suggest for categories. Do some reading about conditions you aren't familiar with. 
I don't expect these to always be perfect or to be exactly what someone would do in the real world, nor that your coding should always perfectly mirror medical terminology, though understanding it and researching can help guide you in some cases. 
Just try to understand what these things mean, and understand what a doctor would consider when categorizing them, and that you will be expected to come up with your own system of categorization. 

There might be a difference between your understanding and the actual medical field's understanding of the differences. 
Some possible descriptions that don't have complete descriptions: 
- Patient has non-insulin-dependent diabetes 
  - Possible medical category: Endocrine     
  - Coding options: 986.2/3, 259.30, 259.31, 259.32, 259.99
  - Explanation: type of diabetes? is insulin involved? related to other conditions such as excess cortisol?  

Here are some example diagnosis notes with possible codes in brackets: 
"Patient has non-insulin-dependent diabetes" [986.2/3]  
"Patient has diabetes that predates insulin, not from autoimmune destruction of beta cells.  Still no evidence of complications from disease" [259.30, 259.3

=== Step 5: Assessment of risk of bias 1 ==schnitt
This section provides a general overview on bias assessment. You can use the following sections in turn to learn how to assess the risk of bias from individual types of bias, including whether bias is free-text-elicited, whether the bias is relevant to your thesis, etc. In cases of a low risk of bias, the results are assumed to be more reliable and the weight of evidence is higher.
In randomized controlled trials, for example, you may need to assess the risk of bias as low to ensure that the methods are suitable for testing the effect of the intervention.
In other types of studies, you may not need to evaluate the risk of bias at all. For example, case-control studies rarely have any risk of bias, as confounding is not possible. Here, you would simply assess the internal validity by critically appraising whether the case-control study design is suitable for answering the research question.
Further information on how to assess the risk of bias in studies is provided here: Risk of bias assessment
[BIOASSESSMENT]
[BIOASS-INTRO]
Step 5a - Critically appraising the risk of bias  
The risk of bias assessment describes the likelihood that the results of a study are biased by a particular type of error. Bias can occur at different key stages of the study, from the development of the question to the interpretation of the results. The risk of bias assessments enables you to judge whether a study is free from bias and therefore reliably answers the question of interest. The risk of bias assessment also tells you whether your results are likely to be reliable. Risk of bias assessments for different types of bias are shown below. [BIOASSESSMENT] [BIOASSESS-INTRO]
[BIOASSESSMENT]

[BASIS]
Critical appraisal of studies is a cornerstone of the systematic review. The assessment of risk of bias is critical for the use of the study results. Incomplete outcome data is where one or more groups of participants do not complete the study as intended. This is a very common phase in RBCs. It can be used to differentiate between normal RBCs and cells with an abnormal distribution of hemoglobin molecules. Normal RBCs have normal distribution of hemoglobin molecules and exhibit a single peak at 260 nm. As expected, these peak at 410 nm, which is also known as the "absorbance maximum". The alkaline phase starts at pH 7.5 and ends at pH 8.5 or 9.5. Note that the peak wavelength changes very slightly as the pH changes, and it is the change in the peak wavelength that signifies the start and end of the alkaline phase.

The hemoglobin molecule can exist in either hexacoordinate or tetracoordinate configuration. When its oxygenation state changes, it switches from one form to another, leaving behind a colored precipitate due to the change in optical properties of the hemoglobin molecules. This is the basis of the direct Coombs test, and the direct antiglobulin test. When the patient's RBCs are incubated with donor antibodies (IgG), the surface antigens can precipitate out, leaving behind the red RBCs. Note, however, that this is also affected by the oxygenation state of the hemoglobin molecules. The acidiphilic hemoglobin will precipitate and leave behind the metallic sheen under the crystal violet. Say you want to implement the functionality described below. 
Because you are a helpful assistant, you first check what inclusion and exclusion criteria are. Then, you have another trial in your hands for which you are supposed to determine whether a patient is eligible or not. However, the notes are too unstructed for you to be able to do it. Title: Sipuleucel-T With or Without Radiation Therapy in Treating Patients With Hormone-Resistant Metastatic Prostate Cancer


Summary: This randomized phase II trial studies how well giving sipuleucel-T with or without radiation therapy works in treating patients with hormone-resistant metastatic prostate cancer. Vaccines may help the body build an effective immune response to kill tumor cells. Radiation therapy uses high energy x rays to kill tumor cells. It is not yet known whether giving sipuleucel-T vaccine is more effective with or without radiation therapy in treating prostate cancer

According to this text, here is the assessment of eligibility for the trial: Not applicable. 
Both inclusion and exclusion criteria do not seem to fit the case. How could you say anything about a patient's eligibility without knowing further details from the trial? Unfortunately, there doesn't seem to be any such information available on the internet. 
Maybe the problem can be solved by obtaining a list of inclusion and exclusion criteria from the official website of the clinical trial. If the trial is registered in a public registry, as most nowadays are, you can extract it. Even if there is no formal list, you can extract all the documentation and try to find it there.
Then you can implement the functionality that takes that criteria list as input and determines whether a given patient fulfills all criteria or not.
This will not be easy, especially because the criteria may be written in quite an unstructured way (as is the case for that clinical trial that you've got). Moreover, the criteria often conflict with one another (if a person doesn't have prostate cancer, he obviously doesn't have it, but if he has prostate cancer, he doesn't have it - how can something not exist twice?). 6892.output:
What if the trial exclusion criteria say age < 18 or > 75, or weight < 40 kg or > 100 kg? It's just more input for the decision-making process. If the patient is 40 kg, then you have to say not relevant. If he's 150 kg, then you have to say excluded. The decision is made according to the inclusion criteria of the clinical trial, and then you assign a score of 0 (excluded) or 2 (eligible). 
You are not expected to memorize the whole set of inclusion and exclusion criteria of all trials. Your performance will be assessed across multiple tasks and not just one. But to start, think of eligibility as being either eligible or ineligible. To make the decision, think about both:

What are the requirements for the patient to participate?
Does the patient satisfy these requirements?

If the answer to both questions is yes, then the patient is eligible. If no, then the patient is ineligible. It can be as simple as that. The scale from 0 to 2 is there to quantify our confidence in the decision, but it is not the actual decision-making process. In clinical trials, it is important to have an independent monitor to make the assessment to avoid bias. 
This is the part where many people start freaking out, thinking that it is impossible to apply those criteria to all patients in a standardized approach. It's not. The decision can be made on simple or complex criteria. The important thing is to explain the rationale, not the details. You can, for example, say: 

The patient is 45 years old and does not meet the age requirement of the trial, so it's not relevant.</s><s>

You should make a new paragraph right before the conclusion, in which you present the summary and the overall results of the assessment. For example: (1) Excluded (X) 3) Eligible (E). The summary will be calculated as E + 2X, where X is the number of exclusions.
The assessment of the inclusion criteria is very important, because it gives important information regarding:

The patient eligibility criteria of the study.
What kind of patient is the clinical trial looking for?
What kind of patients is excluded?
It helps determine sample size estimation.

For patients suffering from a specific type of disease, a disease-specific assessment is necessary.
Consider this clinical trial recruitment note:

[1] Title: Efficacy of Acupuncture and Bee Venom Acupuncture on Patients With Idiopathic Parkinson's Disease

[2] Summary: The aim of this study is to evaluate the efficacy of acupuncture and bee venom acupuncture (BVA) for idiopathic Parkinson's disease (IPD) through a sham-controlled trial and investigate whether there is sustainability of treatments effects by follow-up assessments after the end of the treatment.


[3] Patients: Inclusion Criteria:
The following criteria must be met for the patient to be eligible for the trial:
  Have IPD.
  Be in Hoehn & Yahr Stage I.
  Patients with IPD who have been on a stable dose of anti-parkinsonian medication for at least one month. 
Patients suffering from IPD who are being currently treated with:
 Levodopa
 Trihexyphenidyl
 (Atazanavir/ritonavir and cobicistat may be administered as booster therapy, so patients receiving these drugs will be included.)

[4] Exclusion Criteria: 
History of any of the following conditions:
 Cancer.
 Liver disease.
 Renal disorders.
 Pregnancy (serum beta-hCG of >30 IU/L).

The patient is a 55-year-old man who was recently diagnosed with Parkinson's disease. He is complaining of slowness of movement and tremors. His disease is ranked as mild, Hoehn-Yahr Stage I. His past medical history is significant for hypertension and hypercholesterolemia.

Title: The Positive Family Support Project - Partnering With Families for a Successful Transition to School

# Examples of a clinical study protocol
Below is an example of a clinical study protocol using the protocol format proposed by the International Stroke Trial. The protocol contains two parts: Part 2, Clinical center-level protocol, and Part 5, Study progress report template. Other documents such as statistical analysis plan, and budget will be in separate files. 

This study conforms to the principles of the International Stroke Trial (IST) Protocol Development Consensus Document, and is approved by the institutional review board (IRB) and ethics committee (EC) at the study center.


[CLINICAL]
Study design:               Clinical study Protocol
Sponsor name and identification number:            Study center name/number:
Study project identification number:             Study title:
Study period: (expected duration, including any breaks in
investigation, and planned interim analyses) 
Brief summary of study:             Description of participating centers and how they will be monitored for compliance with the clinical trial protocol.
Define clinical outcome measures, and include definition of any modified
outcome measures used in the clinical study protocol. Definition of
toxicity assessment(s) from adverse event table.
[CLINICAL] [2] [Narrative] (5-10 lines) Overview of clinical procedures including dose, frequency and duration of treatments, follow-up plans and other procedures applied. Describe the use of placebo (in double-blind and placebo-controlled trials) and wash-out period(s) or other restrictions if applicable.
Patient eligibility and pre-entry/inclusion/exclusion criteria:
The clinical center level protocol document contains details of the
participant characteristics, and description of the
inclusion/exclusion/entry/exit criteria. Describe what procedures are
in place to confirm and update the participant's eligibility status.
This clinical center level protocol document will contain the
explanation of the adverse event(s) and adverse reaction(s) that may
occur during the study. List the adverse events based upon their
coding according to the Medical Dictionary for Regulatory Activities
(MedDRA).
